ce:section.ce:para:
In order to investigate the optical properties of the white light-emitting CD/DAP solution, UV-Vis absorption and photoluminescence (PL) studies were carried out. For the distinction of all UV-Vis signals in the spectrum of the mixture and in order to assign each peak to the right component, it is firstly necessary to record the single spectrum of pure DAP without CDs. In order to confirm the structure of the synthesized DAP, UV-Vis absorption data of DAP from literature serve as a reference. However, different references do not show the same absorption bands for DAP in the visible range. Three different signals of DAP were found and assigned: 417 nm, 426 nm and 451 nm [39,50,51]. Our results show that DAP exhibits all these absorption bands, depending on the pH value of the solution (Fig. 4
                        ). All UV-Vis peaks are assigned to the π-π* transition between the phenazine ring and the non-binding electrons of nitrogen in the NH2-group. Interestingly, three different positions of the absorption bands (418 nm, 430 nm and 450 nm) can be seen in the spectrum. Hence, all absorption bands for DAP, which were found in literature, could be confirmed and assigned to different pH values. These three peak positions indicate three different protonated molecular structures of DAP. The higher the number of resonance structures for each protonation degree, the broader the absorption band (at very low pH the DAP spectrum shows a shoulder peak at 475 nm) and the longer the absorption wavelength in the UV-Vis spectrum (Figs. 4 and 5
                        ).
